# IOT-ML — IoT Anomaly Detection System

A real-time IoT sensor anomaly detection pipeline using MQTT, InfluxDB, Isolation Forest ML, and a live web dashboard.

---

## Architecture

```
sim.py ──MQTT──► subscriber.py ──► InfluxDB
                                       │
                                   api.py (ML)
                                   Isolation Forest
                                       │
                                  app.js (Backend)
                                  Express + SSE
                                       │
                                  index.html (Dashboard)
                                  Live Anomaly Detection
```

---

## Features

- **Real-time sensor simulation** — temperature, humidity, CO₂ over MQTT
- **Time-series storage** — InfluxDB for all sensor readings and anomaly logs
- **CSV logging** — every reading appended to sensor_data.csv
- **ML anomaly detection** — Isolation Forest trained on live InfluxDB data
- **Auto-retraining** — model retrains every 5 minutes as new data arrives
- **Model persistence** — trained model saved to disk, loads instantly on restart
- **Severity levels** — anomalies classified as LOW / HIGH / CRITICAL
- **Live dashboard** — SSE streaming, real-time gauges, sensor history chart
- **Anomaly log** — all detected anomalies with timestamp, values, and score
- **CSV export** — one-click download of sensor history from the dashboard
- **Environment variables** — secrets stored in .env, never hardcoded

---

## Tech Stack

| Layer | Technology |
|---|---|
| Sensor Simulation | Python, paho-mqtt |
| Message Broker | Mosquitto (MQTT) |
| Time-Series DB | InfluxDB 2.7 |
| ML Service | Python, Flask, scikit-learn (Isolation Forest) |
| Backend API | Node.js, Express |
| Frontend | HTML, CSS, JavaScript, Chart.js |

---

## Project Structure

```
IOT-ML/
├── simulator/
│   ├── sim.py              # Generates fake sensor data over MQTT
│   ├── subscriber.py       # Receives MQTT data → InfluxDB + CSV
│   └── sensor_data.csv     # Auto-generated sensor log
├── ml-service/
│   └── src/
│       ├── api.py          # Flask ML service (Isolation Forest)
│       ├── model.pkl       # Saved trained model (auto-generated)
│       ├── scaler.pkl      # Saved scaler (auto-generated)
│       └── req.txt         # Python dependencies
├── backend/
│   └── src/
│       ├── app.js          # Express server + SSE streaming
│       └── service.js      # ML service API calls
├── frontend/
│   └── index.html          # Live dashboard
├── .env                    # Environment variables (never commit this)
└── README.md
```

---

## Prerequisites

- Python 3.10+
- Node.js 18+
- [InfluxDB 2.7](https://dl.influxdata.com/influxdb/releases/influxdb2-2.7.11-windows.zip)
- [Mosquitto MQTT Broker](https://mosquitto.org/download/)

---

## Setup & Installation

### 1. Clone the repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/Kunal-OO7/IOT-ML.git
cd IOT-ML
```

### 2. Configure environment variables

Create a `.env` file in the project root and in `ml-service/src/`:

```env
INFLUX_URL=http://localhost:8086
INFLUX_TOKEN=your-influxdb-token
INFLUX_ORG=your-org-name
INFLUX_BUCKET=iot_sensors
```

### 3. Install Python dependencies

```bash
pip install paho-mqtt influxdb-client flask numpy scikit-learn python-dotenv joblib
```

### 4. Install Node.js dependencies

```bash
cd backend
npm install
```

### 5. Set up InfluxDB

1. Download and extract InfluxDB 2.7
2. Run `.\influxd.exe` from the extracted folder
3. Open `http://localhost:8086`
4. Create an account, set org name and bucket name as `iot_sensors`
5. Copy your API token and paste it in `.env`

### 6. Start Mosquitto

```bash
# Run as administrator
net start mosquitto
```

---

## Running the Project

Open **4 separate terminals** and run in this order:

**Terminal 1 — Subscriber**
```bash
cd IOT-ML
python simulator/subscriber.py
```

**Terminal 2 — ML Service**
```bash
cd IOT-ML/ml-service/src
python api.py
```

**Terminal 3 — Simulator**
```bash
cd IOT-ML
python simulator/sim.py
```

**Terminal 4 — Backend**
```bash
cd IOT-ML/backend
node src/app.js
```

Open `http://localhost:3000` in your browser.

---

## ML Model

The anomaly detection uses **Isolation Forest** from scikit-learn.

| Parameter | Value | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `n_estimators` | 100 | Number of trees in the forest |
| `contamination` | 0.07 | Expected anomaly rate (7%) |
| `MIN_SAMPLES` | 50 | Minimum records before first training |
| `RETRAIN_INTERVAL` | 300s | Retrains every 5 minutes if new data exists |

**Severity levels based on anomaly score:**

| Score | Severity |
|---|---|
| < -0.6 | CRITICAL |
| -0.6 to -0.4 | HIGH |
| > -0.4 | LOW |

The model is saved to `model.pkl` and `scaler.pkl` after every training run. On restart, it loads from disk instantly without needing to retrain.

---

## API Endpoints

| Method | Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|---|
| GET | `/api/latest` | Latest sensor reading |
| GET | `/api/history` | Last 5 minutes of readings |
| GET | `/api/detect` | Run anomaly detection |
| GET | `/api/anomalies` | Anomaly history (last 1 hour) |
| GET | `/api/stream` | SSE live stream (updates every 3s) |
| GET | `/health` | ML service health check |
| GET | `/model-status` | Model training status |

---

## Dashboard

The live dashboard at `http://localhost:3000` shows:

- **Live gauges** — real-time temperature, humidity, CO₂ with color-coded anomaly states
- **Sensor history chart** — last 5 minutes of all three sensor readings
- **Anomaly log** — running list of detected anomalies with severity, values, and score
- **Export button** — download current sensor history as CSV

---

## Data Flow

```
Every reading  →  CSV file  +  InfluxDB (sensor_readings measurement)
Anomaly only   →  InfluxDB (anomalies measurement) + Dashboard alert
```

---

## Key Numbers

- **~86,400 data points/day** at 1 reading per second
- **Sub-3 second** alert latency (sensor → dashboard)
- **6 independent services** running concurrently
- **4 REST endpoints** + 1 SSE streaming endpoint
- **3 sensor fields** monitored simultaneously (temp, humidity, CO₂)
- **10% spike rate** in simulated data

